{#
  Inverse Instruction Synthesis
  ─────────────────────────────
  Given two code snippets (old and new file contents from a commit), the LLM
  reverse-engineers a common explanation and a natural-language instruction
  that would plausibly lead a developer to write either snippet.

  No system prompt is used — user-only message.

  Template variables
  ──────────────────
    language      : str   – programming language
    old_contents  : str   – file contents before the commit
    new_contents  : str   – file contents after the commit
    problem_style : str   – one of "graduate course assignment",
                            "quora question", "stackoverflow question",
                            "google search query", "programming contest problem"

  Produces: user message only (no system prompt).
#}
{% block user %}
You are given two snippets in {{ language }} that solve a {{ problem_style }}. These are specified between the [EXAMPLE1] and [/EXAMPLE1] and the [EXAMPLE2] and [/EXAMPLE2] tags as illustrated below:


[EXAMPLE1]

```{{ language }}
{{ old_contents }}
```

[/EXAMPLE1]


[EXAMPLE2]

```{{ language }}
{{ new_contents }}
```

[/EXAMPLE2]


While we are in possession of the resultant solution code snippets, the original problem/query has been stripped away. You are required to:

Firstly, please provide a single common explanation as to what the provided code snippets accomplish in your own words and ensure that the explanation is enclosed between [EXPLAIN] and [/EXPLAIN] tags as illustrated below:

[EXPLAIN]

{{'{{'}}Explanation goes here{{'}}'}}

[/EXPLAIN]

Secondly, You must craft a {{ problem_style }}-style instruction that would sufficiently identifiably lead a mid-tier to experienced developer to converge on the code snippet provided. Make sure to not copy the original provided snippet into the instruction. Finally, provide the instruction you craft between [INSTRUCTION] and [/INSTRUCTION] tags as illustrated below:

[INSTRUCTION]

{{'{{'}}Instruction goes here{{'}}'}}

[/INSTRUCTION]
{% endblock %}
